00:13:55.150 --> 00:13:56.740
But actually, the
seat of your pants

00:13:56.740 --> 00:13:59.140
is primarily your inner
ear is what's giving you

00:13:59.140 --> 00:14:01.660
all these indications.

00:14:01.660 --> 00:14:03.190
So there's a lot
of things that can

00:14:03.190 --> 00:14:05.145
contribute to disorientation.

00:14:05.145 --> 00:14:06.520
So we already
talked a little bit

00:14:06.520 --> 00:14:08.352
about spatial disorientation.

00:14:08.352 --> 00:14:10.060
Well, there are a lot
of things that-- we

00:14:10.060 --> 00:14:12.520
talked about the
vestibular system, which

00:14:12.520 --> 00:14:13.600
is that inner ear.

00:14:13.600 --> 00:14:18.370
But also even visual
cues can cause

00:14:18.370 --> 00:14:21.340
you to have spatial
disorientation, and then

00:14:21.340 --> 00:14:23.290
the feeling on your
skin, so, you know,

00:14:23.290 --> 00:14:27.950
how much you're pressuring
against the seat, for example.

00:14:27.950 --> 00:14:31.120
So one thing about
spatial disorientation

00:14:31.120 --> 00:14:35.290
is that when you're flying and
you're looking out the window,

00:14:35.290 --> 00:14:38.020
your eyes are a big part
of your orientation.

00:14:38.020 --> 00:14:39.730
So you're looking
at the horizon,

00:14:39.730 --> 00:14:42.040
and if the horizon is tilted,
you think you're turning.

00:14:42.040 --> 00:14:44.930
That's how you determine
what's going on.

00:14:44.930 --> 00:14:46.360
But there are a
lot of false cues

00:14:46.360 --> 00:14:49.780
you can get from
looking outside.

00:14:49.780 --> 00:14:53.070
So one thing is that--

00:14:53.070 --> 00:14:56.620
and we spent a little bit of
time talking about IFR flight

00:14:56.620 --> 00:14:59.650
earlier today, where you
can't see outside the airplane

00:14:59.650 --> 00:15:01.750
and you're just relying
on your instruments.

00:15:01.750 --> 00:15:04.030
Well, it's also good
to do a reference

00:15:04.030 --> 00:15:06.910
check of your instruments
because of some of the tricks

00:15:06.910 --> 00:15:09.500
your eyes can play on you.

00:15:09.500 --> 00:15:13.720
So, for example, if there
is a low cloud layer that's

00:15:13.720 --> 00:15:16.900
kind of tilted, the
horizon might look tilted

00:15:16.900 --> 00:15:17.955
and may not look flat.

00:15:17.955 --> 00:15:20.080
And you might think you're
tilted when you're flat.

00:15:20.080 --> 00:15:22.740
Or you might think you're
flat when you're tilted.

00:15:22.740 --> 00:15:24.620
There is also other--

00:15:24.620 --> 00:15:29.570
because of the motion in your
inner ear when you actually

00:15:29.570 --> 00:15:32.420
have a motion in one direction,
if you actually turn over,

00:15:32.420 --> 00:15:36.200
if you bend your head down,
so let's say you're writing

00:15:36.200 --> 00:15:38.120
with a pencil
while you're flying

00:15:38.120 --> 00:15:41.000
and you dropped your pencil,
well, when you bend down,

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:44.550
you actually feel emotions
that don't actually exist.

00:15:44.550 --> 00:15:46.760
You might think you're
sort of tumbling.

00:15:46.760 --> 00:15:49.520
And so that's really not good.

00:15:49.520 --> 00:15:51.020
Actually, if you
fly out of Hanscom,

00:15:51.020 --> 00:15:53.000
you have to wear a badge anyway.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:54.380
And so you have a lanyard.

00:15:54.380 --> 00:15:57.500
Maybe you clip your
pencil to that lanyard

00:15:57.500 --> 00:15:59.000
or do whatever you
can such that you

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.670
can reach everything you need
to reach without physically

00:16:01.670 --> 00:16:03.020
bending over.

00:16:03.020 --> 00:16:06.530
Or if you have a
co-pilot that is also

00:16:06.530 --> 00:16:08.750
could be a pilot in
command or safety pilot,

00:16:08.750 --> 00:16:11.090
you can ask them
to take control.

00:16:11.090 --> 00:16:13.490
And we talked about positive
exchange of controls.

00:16:13.490 --> 00:16:15.440
Ask them to take
control of the aircraft

00:16:15.440 --> 00:16:17.750
before you reach down
to pick up something,

00:16:17.750 --> 00:16:20.210
because it can have a more
significant effect than you

00:16:20.210 --> 00:16:22.810
think it will.

00:16:22.810 --> 00:16:27.640
And I will reserve some of
the aerobatic talk for Mark

00:16:27.640 --> 00:16:30.760
to discuss some of these
with you in more detail.

00:16:33.143 --> 00:16:34.810
PHILIP GREENSPUN:
Tina was talking trash

00:16:34.810 --> 00:16:35.780
about the autopilot.

00:16:35.780 --> 00:16:39.280
But that's also a good
argument for if you

00:16:39.280 --> 00:16:41.140
have to bend down and
get something, take

00:16:41.140 --> 00:16:43.057
your hands off the
controls completely, that's

00:16:43.057 --> 00:16:46.330
better than leaving them on
while you're fishing around

00:16:46.330 --> 00:16:47.150
for something.

00:16:47.150 --> 00:16:49.660
And if you have an
autopilot, yet better.

00:16:51.863 --> 00:16:54.280
TINA SRIVASTAVA: I think the
autopilot is a very important

00:16:54.280 --> 00:16:56.050
tool to use when you're flying.

00:16:56.050 --> 00:16:58.030
I was just cautioning
against it--

00:16:58.030 --> 00:17:01.900
again, when I was flying on my
