00:17:14.470 --> 00:17:16.210
So this is something
once you're flying,

00:17:16.210 --> 00:17:17.710
and you can even
ask your instructor

00:17:17.710 --> 00:17:19.420
to help you with
that, to actually get

00:17:19.420 --> 00:17:21.609
a sense of these
disorientation, you

00:17:21.609 --> 00:17:24.760
can try you know climbing
while accelerating, climbing

00:17:24.760 --> 00:17:27.099
while turning, these
different types of motions,

00:17:27.099 --> 00:17:29.163
and also consider
moving your head,

00:17:29.163 --> 00:17:31.330
making sure the other person
has the flight controls

00:17:31.330 --> 00:17:34.300
to experience some
of these motions.

00:17:34.300 --> 00:17:36.190
Or if you like,
over near, I think,

00:17:36.190 --> 00:17:39.250
Building 33 or Building
35, they have a centrifuge,

00:17:39.250 --> 00:17:43.680
and you can experience a
lot of these things as well.

00:17:43.680 --> 00:17:46.410
So how do you deal with
all these disorientation

00:17:46.410 --> 00:17:47.710
that are happening?

00:17:47.710 --> 00:17:50.160
One is just being aware of
the causes of them help,

00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:53.070
making sure you know
that they're there,

00:17:53.070 --> 00:17:57.100
getting briefings in advance
so you know what's happening.

00:17:57.100 --> 00:18:00.088
And, really, try to avoid
sudden head movements

00:18:00.088 --> 00:18:00.880
when you're flying.

00:18:00.880 --> 00:18:03.420
So we've talked about scanning
and looking for traffic,

00:18:03.420 --> 00:18:06.420
but avoid very sudden head
movements while you're flying,

00:18:06.420 --> 00:18:07.710
because you are moving.

00:18:07.710 --> 00:18:10.235
And it can cause you to
have a lot of effects.

00:18:10.235 --> 00:18:12.360
And then the other thing
is just being well rested,

00:18:12.360 --> 00:18:13.320
eating properly.

00:18:13.320 --> 00:18:15.240
If you're hungry,
if you're tired,

00:18:15.240 --> 00:18:17.280
your body is not at its best.

00:18:17.280 --> 00:18:19.260
It can also contribute.

00:18:19.260 --> 00:18:21.210
So here are just
some more examples

00:18:21.210 --> 00:18:23.903
of the visual illusions.

00:18:23.903 --> 00:18:25.320
And then there are
also times when

00:18:25.320 --> 00:18:26.850
the visual illusions are worse.

00:18:26.850 --> 00:18:29.400
So nighttime, we're going to
have a whole section of night

00:18:29.400 --> 00:18:30.420
flying tomorrow.

00:18:30.420 --> 00:18:32.460
But as it relates
to human factors,

00:18:32.460 --> 00:18:35.490
I will say that you might
think you're coming in

00:18:35.490 --> 00:18:37.920
towards the airport,
but you're actually

00:18:37.920 --> 00:18:41.100
seeing a cluster of lights
that's a city somewhere else.

00:18:41.100 --> 00:18:43.342
You might start going
to the wrong place.

00:18:43.342 --> 00:18:45.300
If you don't keep
referencing your instruments,

00:18:45.300 --> 00:18:48.180
you might not notice that
you're kind of off track.

00:18:48.180 --> 00:18:50.580
I'll give you one tip, though.

00:18:50.580 --> 00:18:52.020
I was flying to Hyannis.

00:18:52.020 --> 00:18:56.370
Hyannis is a city right
at the base of the Cape

00:18:56.370 --> 00:18:58.890
before you go all the way
down the arm of the Cape.

00:18:58.890 --> 00:19:01.380
And there's a great
restaurant there right next

00:19:01.380 --> 00:19:04.290
to the Hyannis airport, a
little French restaurant.

00:19:04.290 --> 00:19:06.870
During the day, they have
kind of little sandwiches

00:19:06.870 --> 00:19:07.530
and pastries.

00:19:07.530 --> 00:19:10.630
And at night, it becomes kind
of a nicer French restaurant.

00:19:10.630 --> 00:19:12.720
So I was actually
flying there at night.

00:19:12.720 --> 00:19:15.960
And coming into Hyannis, I was
having a little bit of issue

00:19:15.960 --> 00:19:18.210
because my heading
indicator kept processing

00:19:18.210 --> 00:19:19.865
and I wasn't sure exactly--

00:19:19.865 --> 00:19:21.240
and things happened
very quickly,

00:19:21.240 --> 00:19:23.847
because I'd been talking
about the Bravo clearance,

00:19:23.847 --> 00:19:25.430
because going from
Bedford over there,

00:19:25.430 --> 00:19:27.780
you're talking to
all these controllers

00:19:27.780 --> 00:19:29.578
and worrying about
your altitude.

00:19:29.578 --> 00:19:30.870
And so there's a lot happening.

00:19:30.870 --> 00:19:33.660
And as I got close to
the Hyannis airport,

00:19:33.660 --> 00:19:36.840
I wasn't exactly sure that I was
going for the-- they have two

00:19:36.840 --> 00:19:38.670
different intersecting runways.

00:19:38.670 --> 00:19:40.380
I wasn't exactly
sure I was lined up

00:19:40.380 --> 00:19:41.790
for the correct runway.

00:19:41.790 --> 00:19:43.800
So I just talked to
the tower controller.

00:19:43.800 --> 00:19:46.090
And I told them that I
was having this issue.

00:19:46.090 --> 00:19:48.900
And so they lit up
the runway that I

00:19:48.900 --> 00:19:51.180
was trying to land at very
bright just for a moment

00:19:51.180 --> 00:19:55.037
so I could get oriented
and get myself situated.

00:19:55.037 --> 00:19:55.870
That was very great.

00:19:55.870 --> 00:20:00.120
So good also to use other
people, whether it's the flight

00:20:00.120 --> 00:20:03.030
service folks or the
tower folks to give you

00:20:03.030 --> 00:20:04.080
help when you need it.

00:20:09.160 --> 00:20:12.092
So this is also just another
thing that happens at night.

00:20:12.092 --> 00:20:14.050
And we'll talk about this
with the night flying

00:20:14.050 --> 00:20:17.970
that sometimes a stationary
light can appear to move.

00:20:17.970 --> 00:20:19.220
And so you have to be careful.

00:20:19.220 --> 00:20:22.200
Don't trust everything you see.

00:20:22.200 --> 00:20:24.240
A big one in terms of
an optical illusion,

00:20:24.240 --> 00:20:28.870
whether it's day or night, is
that if a runway is not flat,

00:20:28.870 --> 00:20:32.700
but it's actually inclined
going up or inclined going down,

00:20:32.700 --> 00:20:35.130
not only as it relates to
performance when we're talking

00:20:35.130 --> 00:20:37.110
about how long it
takes you to land,

00:20:37.110 --> 00:20:39.000
but also as you're
coming in, you

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:42.460
might think that you're a
different place than you are.

00:20:42.460 --> 00:20:46.620
This is also the case if the
runway is wider or narrower

00:20:46.620 --> 00:20:47.610
than you're used to.

00:20:47.610 --> 00:20:50.010
So at Hanscom, you might
have very wide runways.

00:20:50.010 --> 00:20:53.220
If you fly out of Beverly,
you have narrower runways.

00:20:53.220 --> 00:20:55.320
So just that
difference can make you

00:20:55.320 --> 00:20:57.300
think you're at a
different orientation

00:20:57.300 --> 00:20:59.500
or you're higher or
lower than where you are.

00:20:59.500 --> 00:21:00.540
PHILIP GREENSPUN: Tina, can
you go back to that one?

00:21:00.540 --> 00:21:03.087
So basically, they're saying
if the runway is sloped

00:21:03.087 --> 00:21:04.920
and you rely on your
ordinary sight picture,

00:21:04.920 --> 00:21:09.443
you might follow a higher or
lower than standard guide path.

00:21:09.443 --> 00:21:10.860
TINA SRIVASTAVA:
Yeah, absolutely.

00:21:10.860 --> 00:21:14.730
So what it's saying,
the top one is

00:21:14.730 --> 00:21:16.440
showing that, you
know, obviously,

00:21:16.440 --> 00:21:17.790
that's just when it's flat.

00:21:17.790 --> 00:21:20.640
And so when it's
inclined up, you

00:21:20.640 --> 00:21:23.235
might you might try
to be farther away,

00:21:23.235 --> 00:21:24.610
so that you get
the same picture.

00:21:24.610 --> 00:21:28.000
So that the dotted aircraft
is where you should be.

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:31.050
But the solid aircraft is
where you might actually be,

00:21:31.050 --> 00:21:32.610
where you're trying
to compensate

00:21:32.610 --> 00:21:33.615
because of the illusion.

00:21:37.380 --> 00:21:40.230
And then, if there's
a featureless terrain,

00:21:40.230 --> 00:21:42.120
it can really
affect you as well.

00:21:42.120 --> 00:21:44.380
So like right now, we
have a snowy condition.

00:21:44.380 --> 00:21:46.950
So it's harder to
see what's happening.

00:21:46.950 --> 00:21:49.620
It makes it difficult.
And in general, it

00:21:49.620 --> 00:21:55.080
makes you fly a lower
approach, which is not good.

00:21:55.080 --> 00:21:57.138
OK, and then just
a couple more--

00:21:57.138 --> 00:21:58.430
I won't dive into each of them.

00:21:58.430 --> 00:22:02.510
But fog or haze, different types
of things, can cause a mirage

00:22:02.510 --> 00:22:04.040
or can cause an illusion.

00:22:04.040 --> 00:22:07.370
And so you really want to keep
referencing your instruments

00:22:07.370 --> 00:22:10.070
to make sure you are in
fact holding the altitude,

00:22:10.070 --> 00:22:13.870
or use your autopilot
to help you out.

00:22:13.870 --> 00:22:15.790
And, of course, any
reference system,

00:22:15.790 --> 00:22:18.430
so if you have a
VASI or a PAPI, those

00:22:18.430 --> 00:22:21.700
are great tools that even if
it looks like the runways, one

00:22:21.700 --> 00:22:24.520
place or the other, if
the lights are all red,

00:22:24.520 --> 00:22:27.700
you're too low.

00:22:27.700 --> 00:22:29.420
OK, another one is
motion sickness.

00:22:29.420 --> 00:22:32.620
So one thing I want to tell
you about motion sickness

00:22:32.620 --> 00:22:35.162
is when you go up and you take
your first discovery flight,

00:22:35.162 --> 00:22:37.120
you come out of this
class, you're ready to go,

00:22:37.120 --> 00:22:39.070
you might feel a
little bit motion sick.

00:22:39.070 --> 00:22:39.670
And that's OK.

00:22:39.670 --> 00:22:40.780
You're in a tiny airplane.

00:22:40.780 --> 00:22:43.090
It might be bouncing
around a little bit.

00:22:43.090 --> 00:22:45.430
What I'm here to say
is that that goes away.

00:22:45.430 --> 00:22:48.070
You can actually train
your body to get used to it

00:22:48.070 --> 00:22:50.710
and kind of get over
that motion sickness.

00:22:50.710 --> 00:22:53.890
But, unfortunately, you
can lose that tolerance

00:22:53.890 --> 00:22:55.720
that you built up
if you wait a really

00:22:55.720 --> 00:22:57.100
long time between flights.

00:23:01.180 --> 00:23:03.070
I'm at MIT, so I
don't know how much I

00:23:03.070 --> 00:23:04.540
need to tell you about stress.

00:23:04.540 --> 00:23:06.820
I think we all
know about stress.

00:23:06.820 --> 00:23:09.290
We have different ways
of dealing with it.

00:23:09.290 --> 00:23:11.320
But just as much as it
affects your ability

00:23:11.320 --> 00:23:13.690
to take an exam at
MIT, that stress

00:23:13.690 --> 00:23:17.020
can also affect your ability
to fly and think logically

00:23:17.020 --> 00:23:20.393
as you might need to to do
aeronautical decision making.

00:23:20.393 --> 00:23:22.060
PHILIP GREENSPUN: And
that's a good time

00:23:22.060 --> 00:23:23.685
to think about whether
you should bring

00:23:23.685 --> 00:23:25.300
an instructor along on a trip.

00:23:25.300 --> 00:23:29.120
You know, if you're tired or
you're upset about something,

00:23:29.120 --> 00:23:33.218
then be part of
a two-pilot crew.

00:23:33.218 --> 00:23:34.260
TINA SRIVASTAVA: Exactly.

00:23:34.260 --> 00:23:36.280
Fatigue is a big one.

00:23:36.280 --> 00:23:40.060
If you do take my advice and
look at those NTSB reports,

00:23:40.060 --> 00:23:41.880
a large number of
them are talking

00:23:41.880 --> 00:23:46.920
about airline pilots that have
just been flying for 22 hours

00:23:46.920 --> 00:23:50.460
and something happens, whereas
if you really think through it,

00:23:50.460 --> 00:23:53.260
you know, maybe that issue
wouldn't have happened,

00:23:53.260 --> 00:23:57.510
but they're so tired that those
things result in an issue.

00:23:57.510 --> 00:24:01.530
So really be mindful of how much
fatigue can affect your ability

00:24:01.530 --> 00:24:04.430
to fly and what stresses
it puts on the pilot.

00:24:07.750 --> 00:24:10.300
Dehydration and heat
stroke are big ones.

00:24:10.300 --> 00:24:13.780
Here, in this area, it gets
very hot in the summers.

00:24:13.780 --> 00:24:15.460
Make sure to bring
a bottle of water

00:24:15.460 --> 00:24:16.930
with you when you go flying.

00:24:16.930 --> 00:24:18.910
It can be a big issue.

00:24:18.910 --> 00:24:21.520
And, you know, if you're
feeling kind of lightheaded,

00:24:21.520 --> 00:24:23.020
take a drink of water.

00:24:23.020 --> 00:24:26.600
It can make a big difference.

00:24:26.600 --> 00:24:29.420
All right, so no
alcohol or drugs

00:24:29.420 --> 00:24:32.290
while flying or before flying.

00:24:32.290 --> 00:24:34.840
There are some
specific regulations.

00:24:34.840 --> 00:24:36.860
They're much more
strict than driving,

00:24:36.860 --> 00:24:38.370
which I think is a good thing.

00:24:38.370 --> 00:24:42.530
So please take a look at that,
14 CFR Part 91, the blood

00:24:42.530 --> 00:24:45.800
alcohol level and the
time since the last drink.

00:24:45.800 --> 00:24:46.920
It's really not worth it.

00:24:46.920 --> 00:24:48.635
You're flying as
a hobby, for fun,

00:24:48.635 --> 00:24:50.010
don't do something
that's unsafe.

00:24:53.300 --> 00:24:55.490
Some of these are
ways to remember,

00:24:55.490 --> 00:24:58.478
the bottle to throttle
examples here.

00:24:58.478 --> 00:25:00.020
So I'll let you take
a look at those.

00:25:03.220 --> 00:25:04.477
Also, don't carry drugs.

00:25:04.477 --> 00:25:06.310
I don't know if I need
to elaborate on that.

