And so you think you're
looking out your windshield

00:25:28.205 --> 00:25:29.580
and you're scanning
for aircraft,

00:25:29.580 --> 00:25:32.500
but you've sort of
stopped paying attention.

00:25:32.500 --> 00:25:35.250
So one thing that they
recommend you do is actually

00:25:35.250 --> 00:25:38.010
have a series of very
specific eye movements.

00:25:38.010 --> 00:25:38.890
I just moved my head.

00:25:38.890 --> 00:25:40.265
But, again, don't
move your head.

00:25:40.265 --> 00:25:44.010
But kind of look with
your eyes to scan across,

00:25:44.010 --> 00:25:47.340
so that you're actually
specifically deciding

00:25:47.340 --> 00:25:49.830
and you're specifically
looking and scanning

00:25:49.830 --> 00:25:51.240
the air for other aircraft.

00:25:51.240 --> 00:25:52.830
And tell this to
your passengers.

00:25:52.830 --> 00:25:56.880
You don't have to be a trained
pilot to look for aircraft.

00:25:56.880 --> 00:25:59.160
I always tell all
of my passengers.

00:25:59.160 --> 00:26:00.270
Look out the window.

00:26:00.270 --> 00:26:03.490
Tell me if you see
other aircraft.

00:26:03.490 --> 00:26:08.060
OK, so we're going to dive into
aeronautical decision-making.

00:26:08.060 --> 00:26:13.180
One quick thing I'll say is that
I brought a couple of magazines

00:26:13.180 --> 00:26:14.050
here.

00:26:14.050 --> 00:26:17.240
Although some of them are older,
they have some good content.

00:26:17.240 --> 00:26:20.440
So this one is about
aviation safety.

00:26:20.440 --> 00:26:23.350
For folks today that we're
interested in the talk

00:26:23.350 --> 00:26:25.720
about instrument
flight, there's actually

00:26:25.720 --> 00:26:29.860
a magazine called IFR Refresher
and specifically focuses

00:26:29.860 --> 00:26:32.500
on topics related to
instrument flight.

00:26:32.500 --> 00:26:37.060
And then a number of
these Aviation Safety

00:26:37.060 --> 00:26:39.800
that talk about topics
that I felt were relevant,

00:26:39.800 --> 00:26:42.940
such as flying with
icing is one of the ones

00:26:42.940 --> 00:26:45.910
here and flying at night.

00:26:45.910 --> 00:26:48.670
And then there's a
general IFR magazine

00:26:48.670 --> 00:26:51.700
that just talks about some
good articles about how

00:26:51.700 --> 00:26:55.570
you handle your skills in
flying instrument approaches,

00:26:55.570 --> 00:26:57.670
such as ILS.

00:26:57.670 --> 00:27:02.650
So these are kind of first
come, first serve over here.

00:27:02.650 --> 00:27:04.900
So aeronautical
decision-making--

00:27:04.900 --> 00:27:08.660
so how you make decisions
when you're in the cockpit

00:27:08.660 --> 00:27:12.910
can really affect how
you successfully exit

00:27:12.910 --> 00:27:16.390
a very negative situations.

00:27:16.390 --> 00:27:18.880
So whether it's what we were
just talking about with regard

00:27:18.880 --> 00:27:23.050
to having spatial disorientation
or having carbon monoxide

00:27:23.050 --> 00:27:25.760
poisoning versus
an engine failure

00:27:25.760 --> 00:27:28.390
or specific issue
or a weather issue,

00:27:28.390 --> 00:27:30.910
the way that you go
about making a decision

00:27:30.910 --> 00:27:34.940
can significantly
impact the outcome.

00:27:34.940 --> 00:27:38.230
So we're going to talk about
decision-making, hazards,

00:27:38.230 --> 00:27:41.950
how we go about evaluating
risks, and having

00:27:41.950 --> 00:27:45.210
personal checklists.

00:27:45.210 --> 00:27:48.160
So in aeronautical
decision-making,

00:27:48.160 --> 00:27:50.160
one thing to think
about is just that there

00:27:50.160 --> 00:27:52.890
is a way that you
can teach someone

00:27:52.890 --> 00:27:54.850
how to make good decisions.

00:27:54.850 --> 00:27:56.940
So in addition to learning
about your airplane

00:27:56.940 --> 00:27:59.610
and learning how to
fly, one thing that

00:27:59.610 --> 00:28:01.530
throughout your pilot
training is that you'll

00:28:01.530 --> 00:28:05.650
learn how to make decisions.

00:28:05.650 --> 00:28:09.350
So crew resource management
is one specific aspect.

00:28:09.350 --> 00:28:11.560
And we've been alluding
to that all day,

00:28:11.560 --> 00:28:15.070
talking about how to
use either your co-pilot

00:28:15.070 --> 00:28:17.140
or whoever it is that's
sitting next to you

00:28:17.140 --> 00:28:21.160
in the plane or your
other passengers as well.

00:28:21.160 --> 00:28:23.440
There are a number of
aircraft that we talk about,

00:28:23.440 --> 00:28:25.810
and we discuss the
FAA regulations

00:28:25.810 --> 00:28:27.970
earlier about
mandated requirements

00:28:27.970 --> 00:28:31.030
to have a co-pilot or
sometimes other folks.

00:28:31.030 --> 00:28:33.640
But there even people
outside your cockpit

00:28:33.640 --> 00:28:36.250
that you could rely on--
air traffic controllers,

00:28:36.250 --> 00:28:39.190
we talked about, flight
service stations, for example.

00:28:41.800 --> 00:28:44.770
So again really think
about when you're

00:28:44.770 --> 00:28:49.510
flying, although the FAA might
require just a crew of one,

00:28:49.510 --> 00:28:51.960
whether you really are
all alone or there are

00:28:51.960 --> 00:28:53.500
other people you can rely on.

00:28:56.280 --> 00:28:59.610
So there are a lot of aspects
to making good decisions.

00:28:59.610 --> 00:29:03.510
And this is part of why pilots
love talking to other pilots.

00:29:03.510 --> 00:29:06.030
They also just like
discussing if they

00:29:06.030 --> 00:29:07.830
encountered an
issue, how they went

00:29:07.830 --> 00:29:09.600
about dealing with that issue.

00:29:09.600 --> 00:29:12.090
And talking to other people
about their experiences

00:29:12.090 --> 00:29:14.520
is actually a good way to learn.

00:29:14.520 --> 00:29:16.080
One thing you
should also know is

00:29:16.080 --> 00:29:18.450
about your personal attitudes.

00:29:18.450 --> 00:29:21.570
I think that might have
been another reason Laz,

00:29:21.570 --> 00:29:25.890
our F-22 pilot yesterday was
so against Top Gun, the concept

00:29:25.890 --> 00:29:30.930
of being a very arrogant person
that violates the rules is

00:29:30.930 --> 00:29:34.560
really not a good stereotype
for a pilot because people

00:29:34.560 --> 00:29:38.130
that fly like that are more
likely to have accidents.

00:29:38.130 --> 00:29:40.470
How you can modify
your behavior,

00:29:40.470 --> 00:29:43.150
how to recognize and
cope with stress,

00:29:43.150 --> 00:29:45.690
we could certainly
use that here at MIT.

00:29:45.690 --> 00:29:48.360
And then how to really
assess risks properly,

00:29:48.360 --> 00:29:50.640
we talked about
weather as an example.

00:29:50.640 --> 00:29:53.430
How do you know if you have
the right weather information?

00:29:53.430 --> 00:29:55.980
Have you evaluated a
risk appropriately?

00:29:55.980 --> 00:29:59.200
And we've really tried to give
you pointers and cues for that.

00:29:59.200 --> 00:30:02.580
Especially if they tell you
VFR flight not advisable,

00:30:02.580 --> 00:30:03.540
it's not advisable.

00:30:03.540 --> 00:30:07.470
That means it's
probably a bad idea.

00:30:07.470 --> 00:30:09.420
So hazards and risks--

00:30:09.420 --> 00:30:13.530
so a hazard is
basically a condition

00:30:13.530 --> 00:30:17.100
or an event, something
that you might encounter,

00:30:17.100 --> 00:30:19.920
whereas risk is
basically your assessment

00:30:19.920 --> 00:30:22.930
of how likely is that risk?

00:30:22.930 --> 00:30:25.380
How likely is that hazard
going to come to be?

00:30:25.380 --> 00:30:28.245
What impact could that
hazard have on your outcome?

00:30:31.030 --> 00:30:33.790
So one thing, again,
is about your attitude.

00:30:33.790 --> 00:30:36.990
So don't be like
those Top Gun pilots.

00:30:36.990 --> 00:30:39.990
If you're very
anti-authority and you say,

00:30:39.990 --> 00:30:43.050
you know, I don't care
even if the weather

00:30:43.050 --> 00:30:46.770
folks said VFR flight not
advisable, I'm a great pilot.

00:30:46.770 --> 00:30:48.090
I can do it any way.

00:30:48.090 --> 00:30:49.800
That type of
attitude is probably

00:30:49.800 --> 00:30:51.900
going to lead you
in unsafe condition.

00:30:51.900 --> 00:30:54.960
It's really not a good idea.

00:30:54.960 --> 00:30:57.920
We also discussed the
concept of personal minimums

00:30:57.920 --> 00:31:00.330
and setting personal
minimums for yourself.

00:31:00.330 --> 00:31:05.150
The reason is that today,
for example, or after you've

00:31:05.150 --> 00:31:07.550
done a little bit
of flying, you might

00:31:07.550 --> 00:31:10.070
have a good sense of what
you're comfortable with.

00:31:10.070 --> 00:31:13.850
You might have gone up with
a lot of gusting winds.

00:31:13.850 --> 00:31:15.680
And so you might
decide that, hey, I

00:31:15.680 --> 00:31:19.460
was a little bit uncomfortable
with winds gusting to 20 knots.

00:31:19.460 --> 00:31:21.950
Even if my aircraft
is capable of it,

00:31:21.950 --> 00:31:24.200
I think that's something
that until I get a little bit

00:31:24.200 --> 00:31:27.010
more experience, I'm going to
set as a personal minimum I

00:31:27.010 --> 00:31:30.020
don't want winds
gusting over 15 knots

00:31:30.020 --> 00:31:32.690
before I decide to take
a flight by myself.

00:31:32.690 --> 00:31:34.580
So you can set your
personal minimums.

00:31:34.580 --> 00:31:36.410
Why are we talking about that?

00:31:36.410 --> 00:31:40.220
Well, the reason is on the
actual day that you're flying,

00:31:40.220 --> 00:31:42.890
you may re-evaluate
the situation.

00:31:42.890 --> 00:31:45.230
You might really want
to go flying that day.

00:31:45.230 --> 00:31:48.560
Maybe you've already arranged
with a friend to come with you.

00:31:48.560 --> 00:31:51.650
Maybe you have a destination
you're really trying to reach.

00:31:51.650 --> 00:31:53.510
Philip described a
number of situations

00:31:53.510 --> 00:31:55.250
where he's flying cross-country.

00:31:55.250 --> 00:31:56.220
He has a plan.

00:31:56.220 --> 00:31:57.410
He has to follow it.

00:31:57.410 --> 00:32:01.320
And he can't really be
away missing several days

00:32:01.320 --> 00:32:02.690
where he was trying to go.

00:32:02.690 --> 00:32:05.960
And so sometimes
in the moment you

00:32:05.960 --> 00:32:08.840
might have an impulsive nature.

00:32:08.840 --> 00:32:11.000
You might decide that
I think I can do it.

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:12.870
I'm sure it's fine.

00:32:12.870 --> 00:32:14.990
So having personal
minimums and actually

00:32:14.990 --> 00:32:17.600
writing those down
are a really good way

00:32:17.600 --> 00:32:19.760
to hold yourself
accountable to what

00:32:19.760 --> 00:32:27.000
you had decided in a calm state
of mind was a good restriction.

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:29.940
So one thing to keep in mind
is the assessment of risk.

00:32:29.940 --> 00:32:33.870
You also shouldn't be
overly risk averse.

00:32:33.870 --> 00:32:37.110
The FAA has guidance on
what type of equipment

00:32:37.110 --> 00:32:38.760
is required in your aircraft.

00:32:38.760 --> 00:32:40.710
So certain things
are that's required.

00:32:40.710 --> 00:32:42.990
If it's not there,
you can't fly.

00:32:42.990 --> 00:32:45.450
But there are other
things that are optional.

00:32:45.450 --> 00:32:47.970
And so if there's a piece of
equipment that's optional,

00:32:47.970 --> 00:32:51.460
that's not functional.

00:32:51.460 --> 00:32:53.760
There's a lot of importance
around understanding

00:32:53.760 --> 00:32:56.070
what is the risk of that
not being operational

00:32:56.070 --> 00:32:56.920
as an example.

00:32:56.920 --> 00:33:00.810
And we'll go through a
checklist in a little bit

00:33:00.810 --> 00:33:03.390
to assess both your
personal state of being,

00:33:03.390 --> 00:33:05.490
your aircraft state of
being, the environment,

00:33:05.490 --> 00:33:08.860
and assessing all
those risks together.

00:33:08.860 --> 00:33:12.720
But for a given risk, you want
to know, one, how likely is it?

00:33:12.720 --> 00:33:15.750
So maybe if you're
talking about weather,

00:33:15.750 --> 00:33:19.200
there is a chance that
a storm will come in.

00:33:19.200 --> 00:33:21.240
There's a chance that it won't.

00:33:21.240 --> 00:33:25.020
Then also the severity, are we
talking about some light rain

00:33:25.020 --> 00:33:25.710
showers?

00:33:25.710 --> 00:33:29.280
Or are we talking about a
very, very dangerous front

00:33:29.280 --> 00:33:31.672
with icing or thunderstorms?

00:33:31.672 --> 00:33:33.630
So that's the difference
between the likelihood

00:33:33.630 --> 00:33:34.830
and the severity.

00:33:34.830 --> 00:33:39.090
Both of those have to be
assessed for a given hazard

00:33:39.090 --> 00:33:42.370
that you encounter when
you assess its risk.

00:33:42.370 --> 00:33:45.490
So there's this way
of checking yourself.

00:33:45.490 --> 00:33:46.990
It's called IMSAFE.

00:33:46.990 --> 00:33:50.460
So this is just
determining just you--

00:33:50.460 --> 00:33:53.460
not the airplane, not the
environment-- as a pilot

00:33:53.460 --> 00:33:54.930
if you're safe to fly.

00:33:54.930 --> 00:33:56.440
So do you have an illness?

00:33:56.440 --> 00:33:59.700
Or are you taking medications
that might affect your ability

00:33:59.700 --> 00:34:00.240
to fly?

00:34:00.240 --> 00:34:02.160
Are you very stressed out?

00:34:02.160 --> 00:34:04.530
Do you have your
thermodynamics final coming up

00:34:04.530 --> 00:34:08.040
and you're really
nervous about it?

00:34:08.040 --> 00:34:11.080
Again, we talked about there
are also legal regulations.

00:34:11.080 --> 00:34:13.679
You can't have alcohol or drugs
that could affect your ability

00:34:13.679 --> 00:34:14.610
to fly.

00:34:14.610 --> 00:34:16.290
Are you just very tired?

00:34:16.290 --> 00:34:18.630
Or really, just are you
very distracted by something

00:34:18.630 --> 00:34:21.449
that's happening?

00:34:21.449 --> 00:34:23.760
The PAVE checklist
is the one I was

00:34:23.760 --> 00:34:25.980
referring to that
actually considers

00:34:25.980 --> 00:34:27.870
all of these different things.

00:34:27.870 --> 00:34:30.630
So the IMSAFE is just the pilot.

00:34:30.630 --> 00:34:33.389
A is referring to the aircraft.

00:34:33.389 --> 00:34:36.030
So this is when we're talking
about are certain things

00:34:36.030 --> 00:34:37.292
different about the aircraft?

00:34:37.292 --> 00:34:39.000
Maybe it's a new
aircraft that you're not

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:40.324
really comfortable with.

00:34:40.324 --> 00:34:41.699
Maybe you're
checked out, but you

00:34:41.699 --> 00:34:44.255
don't have that many hours
in that particular aircraft.

00:34:44.255 --> 00:34:46.380
Or maybe you know we've
talked about the difference

00:34:46.380 --> 00:34:48.300
between steam gauge and G1000.

00:34:48.300 --> 00:34:50.699
Maybe you're really used
to flying steam gauge

00:34:50.699 --> 00:34:51.923
and this is a G1000.

00:34:51.923 --> 00:34:54.090
So there's nothing actually
wrong with the airplane,

00:34:54.090 --> 00:34:55.949
but you may be less comfortable.

00:34:55.949 --> 00:34:57.840
Environmental, so
that could be weather.

00:34:57.840 --> 00:34:59.845
That could be flying
to a new airport.

00:34:59.845 --> 00:35:01.470
That could be flying
to an airport that

00:35:01.470 --> 00:35:02.910
has some special conditions.

00:35:02.910 --> 00:35:04.260
Maybe it's a grass strip.

00:35:04.260 --> 00:35:08.670
You're flying to
Katama, which is a grass

00:35:08.670 --> 00:35:11.923
runway out at Martha's Vineyard
right next to the beach.

00:35:11.923 --> 00:35:12.840
It's really beautiful.

00:35:12.840 --> 00:35:13.710
I recommend it.

00:35:13.710 --> 00:35:17.580
But maybe if it's your first
time, flying to a soft field,

00:35:17.580 --> 00:35:19.620
that could be a concern.

00:35:19.620 --> 00:35:22.955
External pressures, that's what
we were just talking about.

00:35:22.955 --> 00:35:24.330
You're already
committed to being

00:35:24.330 --> 00:35:26.120
somewhere later in the day.

00:35:26.120 --> 00:35:27.990
You've met up with somebody.

00:35:27.990 --> 00:35:28.950
You're with a friend.

00:35:28.950 --> 00:35:30.720
You had decided to
take them flying.

00:35:30.720 --> 00:35:32.730
They really wanted to go.

00:35:32.730 --> 00:35:35.370
But the weather is
looking a little bit iffy.

00:35:35.370 --> 00:35:38.130
So one thing that's good
about this PAVE checklist

00:35:38.130 --> 00:35:40.470
is to kind of put
things in perspective.

00:35:40.470 --> 00:35:45.000
That maybe you're feeling
a little bit stressed out

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:48.900
or distracted about an MIT exam,
but the aircraft is the one

00:35:48.900 --> 00:35:50.530
that you've been flying a lot.

00:35:50.530 --> 00:35:51.780
You're very familiar with it.

00:35:51.780 --> 00:35:53.405
You have a lot of
time on the aircraft.

00:35:53.405 --> 00:35:54.660
Everything is working well.

00:35:54.660 --> 00:35:56.160
You have a good amount of fuel.

00:35:56.160 --> 00:35:57.120
The weather's great.

00:35:57.120 --> 00:35:58.290
It's a beautiful day.

00:35:58.290 --> 00:36:00.150
You're flying to
familiar airports.

00:36:00.150 --> 00:36:02.298
And you don't have any
external pressures that day.

00:36:02.298 --> 00:36:03.840
There's no one you're
trying to meet.

00:36:03.840 --> 00:36:05.590
There's nothing you're
trying to get done.

00:36:05.590 --> 00:36:08.250
So that might be a good day
that, OK, one of these things

00:36:08.250 --> 00:36:12.090
is a little bit iffy, nothing
crossed your minimums,

00:36:12.090 --> 00:36:14.100
but it's just something
that maybe you

00:36:14.100 --> 00:36:15.900
could still go ahead and fly.

00:36:15.900 --> 00:36:17.610
However, if it's
multiple things,

00:36:17.610 --> 00:36:19.690
if it's a different aircraft.

00:36:19.690 --> 00:36:20.880
It's a different location.

00:36:20.880 --> 00:36:22.140
You're having stresses.

00:36:22.140 --> 00:36:24.120
These start becoming
times that you

00:36:24.120 --> 00:36:27.038
want to take these risks even
more seriously, because as they

00:36:27.038 --> 00:36:28.830
come together, it could
affect your ability

00:36:28.830 --> 00:36:31.690
to have a safe flight.

00:36:31.690 --> 00:36:34.230
So just these types
of personal checklists

00:36:34.230 --> 00:36:38.280
are a great way to assess
risk and make decisions

00:36:38.280 --> 00:36:40.200
as you're trying to
decide whether or not

00:36:40.200 --> 00:36:43.243
to go on a flight.

00:36:43.243 --> 00:36:45.410
And these are just a breakdown
of some of the things

00:36:45.410 --> 00:36:48.020
I just said on the
environmental condition.

00:36:48.020 --> 00:36:50.000
So nighttime is also on there.

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:51.980
Tomorrow, we'll talk
about night flying

00:36:51.980 --> 00:36:54.500
in particular and the
fact that basically

00:36:54.500 --> 00:36:57.710
in the US with just your
private pilot's license,

00:36:57.710 --> 00:36:58.970
you can fly at night.

00:36:58.970 --> 00:37:00.710
A lot of other
countries consider

00:37:00.710 --> 00:37:05.540
night flying just as advanced
as instrument flying.

00:37:05.540 --> 00:37:07.190
And you need your
instrument rating

00:37:07.190 --> 00:37:09.560
to fly at night because
of all the concerns

00:37:09.560 --> 00:37:12.560
about not being able to see
much outside your airplane.

00:37:12.560 --> 00:37:14.300
So be mindful that,
you know, it's

00:37:14.300 --> 00:37:16.910
a slightly more challenging
condition to fly in.

00:37:16.910 --> 00:37:18.797
And how does that
affect your ability

00:37:18.797 --> 00:37:21.005
to assess the other risks
that might be taking place?

00:37:23.670 --> 00:37:25.740
I really would
recommend, especially

00:37:25.740 --> 00:37:28.230
when you're first
getting certified,

00:37:28.230 --> 00:37:31.380
you don't really make plans
anywhere near the time

00:37:31.380 --> 00:37:34.540
that you're supposed
to be done flying.

00:37:34.540 --> 00:37:36.540
Most flight schools will
give you a flight block

00:37:36.540 --> 00:37:37.768
of 2 and 1/2 hours.

00:37:37.768 --> 00:37:39.810
Make sure that you don't
have to be anywhere even

00:37:39.810 --> 00:37:41.610
for a few hours after that.

00:37:41.610 --> 00:37:44.335
In case the weather got bad,
you had to land somewhere else,

00:37:44.335 --> 00:37:45.960
you don't want those
external pressures

00:37:45.960 --> 00:37:48.390
affecting your decision-making
when you're in the cockpit.

00:37:51.450 --> 00:37:53.700
This is another way to
think about it in terms

00:37:53.700 --> 00:37:56.970
of this 5 "P" checklist.

00:37:56.970 --> 00:38:01.638
So there are certain
kind of different parts

00:38:01.638 --> 00:38:02.430
through the flight.

00:38:02.430 --> 00:38:04.590
We discussed the
pre-flight, take-off,

00:38:04.590 --> 00:38:07.800
while you're kind of cruising
along, you're descending

00:38:07.800 --> 00:38:09.270
and you're flying,
and it might be

00:38:09.270 --> 00:38:14.520
good to kind of look through
all of these different aspects

00:38:14.520 --> 00:38:17.100
about when you're flying
and kind of checklist

00:38:17.100 --> 00:38:19.327
for yourself to understand
what's happening.

00:38:19.327 --> 00:38:20.910
There are a lot of
different resources

00:38:20.910 --> 00:38:23.610
that talk about aeronautical
decision-making.

00:38:23.610 --> 00:38:25.560
I think one of
the best resources

00:38:25.560 --> 00:38:28.920
is really talking to other
pilots about experiences

00:38:28.920 --> 00:38:30.960
that they've gone
through and learning

00:38:30.960 --> 00:38:33.690
after you go through an
experience reflecting

00:38:33.690 --> 00:38:35.940
afterwards whether it's
through your instructor,

00:38:35.940 --> 00:38:36.880
with your friends.

00:38:36.880 --> 00:38:37.920
You know, what happened?

00:38:37.920 --> 00:38:39.990
What could I have
done differently?

00:38:39.990 --> 00:38:41.582
Was that the right
decision to make?

00:38:41.582 --> 00:38:43.290
So even these little
things, like Phillip

00:38:43.290 --> 00:38:45.600
was talking about
flying with Oxana,

00:38:45.600 --> 00:38:47.520
trying to avoid some weather.

00:38:47.520 --> 00:38:48.500
There was rain.

00:38:48.500 --> 00:38:51.990
Thinking about how he evaluated
that risk of that thunderstorm.

00:38:51.990 --> 00:38:53.490
What could he have
done differently?

00:38:53.490 --> 00:38:54.810
Was that the right decision?

00:38:54.810 --> 00:38:57.180
And in general, making
a conservative decision

00:38:57.180 --> 00:38:58.918
is good, because it's
your life at stake

00:38:58.918 --> 00:38:59.960
that we're talking about.

00:39:02.710 --> 00:39:05.730
All right, so I think we've
talked a lot about this.

00:39:05.730 --> 00:39:09.310
Are there any specific questions
on aeronautical decision-making

00:39:09.310 --> 00:39:10.630
or human factors in general?

00:39:10.630 --> 00:39:11.240
Yes.

00:39:11.240 --> 00:39:12.684
AUDIENCE: You
mentioned currency.

00:39:12.684 --> 00:39:15.585
Is there like a recommended
frequency, or like rule

00:39:15.585 --> 00:39:18.640
of thumb, like how often
you should be flying

00:39:18.640 --> 00:39:20.410
to be maintaining your skills?

00:39:20.410 --> 00:39:22.910
PHILIP GREENSPUN: We're going
to cover that at the very end.

00:39:22.910 --> 00:39:26.230
There's a Cirrus that we put
together this big matrix.

00:39:26.230 --> 00:39:28.540
They don't tell you how
often to fly to practice.

00:39:28.540 --> 00:39:30.130
But they tell you
given how recently

00:39:30.130 --> 00:39:32.170
you've been flying
and practicing,

00:39:32.170 --> 00:39:34.580
here's the kind of weather
that should be challenging.

00:39:34.580 --> 00:39:37.630
TINA SRIVASTAVA: So the question
for those who couldn't hear

00:39:37.630 --> 00:39:39.520
was just about the currency.

00:39:39.520 --> 00:39:44.140
So are there rules about
how often you need to fly?

00:39:44.140 --> 00:39:46.480
And there are rules,
especially related

00:39:46.480 --> 00:39:50.330
to carrying passengers
at night, for example.

00:39:50.330 --> 00:39:52.960
There are certain legal
currency requirements.

00:39:52.960 --> 00:39:56.500
But just as Philip said, there's
also just personal minimums

00:39:56.500 --> 00:39:58.210
that you might want
to set for yourself.

00:39:58.210 --> 00:40:00.490
If you haven't gone
flying for a month,

00:40:00.490 --> 00:40:02.770
you may be legally
current, but may not

00:40:02.770 --> 00:40:05.140
be a good time to take
a bunch of passengers

00:40:05.140 --> 00:40:08.170
to a new destination that
you haven't flown to before.

00:40:08.170 --> 00:40:09.400
PHILIP GREENSPUN: Yeah, so
you remember from yesterday,

00:40:09.400 --> 00:40:11.440
there's that 90 day, three
takeoffs and landings

00:40:11.440 --> 00:40:13.065
within the preceding
90 days before you

00:40:13.065 --> 00:40:14.450
can carry passengers.

00:40:14.450 --> 00:40:15.580
That's a good minimum.

00:40:15.580 --> 00:40:19.510
A lot depends on
the type of aircraft

00:40:19.510 --> 00:40:21.110
and how familiar
you are with it.

00:40:21.110 --> 00:40:24.160
So if you have 500 hours in
a very logically designed

00:40:24.160 --> 00:40:27.310
airplane like the
Cirrus, you know,

00:40:27.310 --> 00:40:29.710
then you're going
to be safe probably

00:40:29.710 --> 00:40:31.460
without flying too often.

00:40:31.460 --> 00:40:33.620
In a more complicated
aircraft, you know,

00:40:33.620 --> 00:40:36.460
that has buttons and
levers just randomly strewn

00:40:36.460 --> 00:40:40.210
across the panel, which seems
to be the industry standard, you

00:40:40.210 --> 00:40:42.010
know, if you haven't
flown it for a month,

00:40:42.010 --> 00:40:43.780
you may actually be
a little bit at sea

00:40:43.780 --> 00:40:46.060
as to where are the flaps?

00:40:46.060 --> 00:40:47.660
Where is the gear?

00:40:47.660 --> 00:40:50.650
So a lot depends on how
many hours of experience

00:40:50.650 --> 00:40:52.990
you have in the type of
aircraft you're going to fly

00:40:52.990 --> 00:40:56.770
and just how inherently
challenging it is to fly.

00:40:56.770 --> 00:41:00.520
The practical
currency requirements

00:41:00.520 --> 00:41:02.650
for a multi-engine
piston airplane

00:41:02.650 --> 00:41:05.500
are going to be very
different from those

00:41:05.500 --> 00:41:07.530
that you might use
in the Piper cub.

00:41:07.530 --> 00:41:10.300
TINA SRIVASTAVA: Yeah, when
we polled the class earlier,

00:41:10.300 --> 00:41:13.300
I think there were
70 of you have really

00:41:13.300 --> 00:41:15.700
only flown once or not at all.

00:41:15.700 --> 00:41:17.740
And so that's a
lot of people that

00:41:17.740 --> 00:41:19.670
don't have flying experience.

00:41:19.670 --> 00:41:22.270
So I would say, you know,
back before I had 200 hours,

00:41:22.270 --> 00:41:25.160
or even before I had 100
hours of flying experience,

00:41:25.160 --> 00:41:27.760
I actually set very strict
currency requirements.

00:41:27.760 --> 00:41:30.850
I had to fly, you know, two
times a week before I really

00:41:30.850 --> 00:41:33.390
felt comfortable
taking up a passenger,

00:41:33.390 --> 00:41:36.850
when I wanted to fly relatively
frequently with an instructor

00:41:36.850 --> 00:41:39.890
and practice stall recovery,
these types of things.

00:41:39.890 --> 00:41:40.960
And I think that's good.

00:41:40.960 --> 00:41:44.242
Make it as much as you need
to in order to be safe.

00:41:44.242 --> 00:41:45.200
PHILIP GREENSPUN: Yeah.

00:41:45.200 --> 00:41:48.040
You could also decide again, if
you haven't flown for a while,

00:41:48.040 --> 00:41:49.840
are you going to fly
an IFR approach down

00:41:49.840 --> 00:41:54.610
to minimums, down at 200 feet
above the runway in the clouds

00:41:54.610 --> 00:41:59.290
by yourself in an airplane with
no autopilot, would be legal?

00:41:59.290 --> 00:42:01.690
Or you're going to say,
look, I'm a little bit rusty,

00:42:01.690 --> 00:42:05.980
so I'm going to only fly
on a fairly calm VFR day

00:42:05.980 --> 00:42:07.300
and get back into it?

00:42:07.300 --> 00:42:10.380
So a lot depends on the
challenge of the flight

00:42:10.380 --> 00:42:11.772
that you're considering.

00:42:14.570 --> 00:42:15.570
Who else has a question?

00:42:18.180 --> 00:42:19.930
I'll tell you one
more little story.

00:42:19.930 --> 00:42:23.550
A friend of mine had a twin
engine airplane, a Cessna 340,

00:42:23.550 --> 00:42:25.410
which is a very
complicated airplane with--

00:42:25.410 --> 00:42:29.380
I think it has six fuel tanks
and all kinds of levers.

00:42:29.380 --> 00:42:32.700
It's pressurized off
the turbo chargers.

00:42:32.700 --> 00:42:35.430
Anyway, one engine
caught on fire.

00:42:35.430 --> 00:42:37.020
So an engine caught on fire.

00:42:37.020 --> 00:42:41.280
He's got four or five people
from his family in the back.

00:42:41.280 --> 00:42:44.640
And he manages to get the fire
out by cutting off the fuel,

00:42:44.640 --> 00:42:46.800
I guess, to the burning engine.

00:42:46.800 --> 00:42:49.140
He's right above Bradley
Field in Connecticut.

00:42:49.140 --> 00:42:52.320
So that's one of the largest
airports actually in the world.

00:42:52.320 --> 00:42:55.240
It's probably among
the top few percent

00:42:55.240 --> 00:42:58.193
of big airports in the world
in terms of physical size.

00:42:58.193 --> 00:42:59.610
They have regular
airline service.

00:42:59.610 --> 00:43:01.193
They have a full-time
fire department.

00:43:01.193 --> 00:43:02.430
They have a control tower.

00:43:02.430 --> 00:43:04.972
They have a runway that's about
as long as Logan's, you know,

00:43:04.972 --> 00:43:08.760
like close to 1
miles long runway.

00:43:08.760 --> 00:43:12.290
So he decides, well,
I've got one engine.

00:43:12.290 --> 00:43:12.915
It's nighttime.

00:43:12.915 --> 00:43:14.518
It was night.

00:43:14.518 --> 00:43:15.810
The controllers are right here.

00:43:15.810 --> 00:43:19.460
Should I just, you know,
spiral down and land

00:43:19.460 --> 00:43:21.410
on one of these huge
runways at Bradley

00:43:21.410 --> 00:43:24.660
and the fire department come
up and meet the airplane?

00:43:24.660 --> 00:43:26.850
Or-- that's option 1.

00:43:26.850 --> 00:43:28.860
Let's see what you guys think.

00:43:28.860 --> 00:43:31.770
Option 2, let me continue
to my home airport

00:43:31.770 --> 00:43:34.490
at Fitchburg, which
is unattended.

00:43:34.490 --> 00:43:37.800
I don't think there's a fire
department that's there.

00:43:37.800 --> 00:43:39.390
There's no control tower.

00:43:39.390 --> 00:43:41.853
The runway is pretty
short, 4,500 feet.

00:43:41.853 --> 00:43:43.770
But on the other hand,
it is the home airport.

00:43:43.770 --> 00:43:45.030
So it's very familiar.

00:43:45.030 --> 00:43:47.610
And he's got one engine left.

00:43:47.610 --> 00:43:51.210
You only need one
engine to descend.

00:43:51.210 --> 00:43:53.194
So what do you
guys think, A or B?

00:43:53.194 --> 00:43:57.702
Land it at Bradley
or go to Pittsburgh?

00:43:57.702 --> 00:43:59.160
OK, what do you
think this guy did?

00:43:59.160 --> 00:44:00.570
AUDIENCE: He went to Fitchburg.

00:44:00.570 --> 00:44:01.700
PHILIP GREENSPUN: He
went to Fitchburg.

00:44:01.700 --> 00:44:03.030
And he wrecked the airplane.

00:44:03.030 --> 00:44:03.900
You know, he landed.

00:44:03.900 --> 00:44:06.555
But I don't know-- it's
twins with one engine.

00:44:06.555 --> 00:44:08.430
They always say the
second engine carries you

00:44:08.430 --> 00:44:09.638
to the scene of the accident.

00:44:09.638 --> 00:44:12.030
We'll talk about that tomorrow.

00:44:12.030 --> 00:44:15.070
So they just are hard--
it's hard to maintain--

00:44:15.070 --> 00:44:17.070
it's hard to keep them
going perfectly straight.

00:44:17.070 --> 00:44:18.987
So, of course, he didn't
go perfectly straight

00:44:18.987 --> 00:44:21.540
down the runway, went off
the side of the runway,

00:44:21.540 --> 00:44:23.250
did some damage to the airplane.

00:44:23.250 --> 00:44:24.690
Nobody was hurt, fortunately.

00:44:24.690 --> 00:44:27.690
The punchline of the story
is he doesn't tell this

00:44:27.690 --> 00:44:31.140
as an example of bad
aeronautical decision-making he

00:44:31.140 --> 00:44:35.070
tells this as a story
of good decisions

00:44:35.070 --> 00:44:37.020
and making good
decisions as a pilot.

00:44:37.020 --> 00:44:38.970
And I'm not really sure why.

00:44:38.970 --> 00:44:40.680
But anyway, I just
wanted to tell you,

00:44:40.680 --> 00:44:42.720
like despite all
those checklists,

00:44:42.720 --> 00:44:45.960
people can have very
different perspectives on what

00:44:45.960 --> 00:44:48.030
constitutes a wise decision.

00:44:48.030 --> 00:44:51.240
But personally, I try to
do-- you know, I have an ATP.

00:44:51.240 --> 00:44:54.480
But I try to do flights whenever
possible that require only

00:44:54.480 --> 00:44:56.470
a student pilot level of skill.

00:44:56.470 --> 00:44:59.000
And that gives me a nice margin.